Almost one-third of unemployed persons in Germany are unable to regularly eat a nutritious meal. Responding to a parliamentary enquiry from the Left party, the Federal Statistics Office reported that 30.3 percent of unemployed people did not have enough money to eat a hearty meal every other day. Read more: Germany's welfare experiment: Sanction-free 'basic security' That amounts to about 5.14 million people over the age of 16, or 7.5 percent of Germany's total population. The data is based on a 2017 EU survey on income, social inclusion and living conditions. Send  Facebook   Twitter   google+   Whatsapp   Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink https://p.dw.com/p/3B2f0 The same survey found that around one-third of Germans over the age of 16 are not in the position to afford an unexpected expense of €1,000 ($1,140), such as paying for car repair or a new washing machine. "Poverty is not a marginal phenomenon in Germany, but runs throughout the population," Left party social policy politician Sabine Zimmermann told the Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung newspaper, which reported the figures. Send  Facebook   Twitter   google+   Whatsapp   Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink https://p.dw.com/p/2rEmh DW editors send out a selection of the day's hard news and quality feature journalism every evening. You can sign up to receive it here.